The first electrical tier, Low Voltage.

With the start of electrical tiers, here is an explanation on Gregtech power:

Voltage - The max EU/t that a machine can operate at and max amount of EU it can accept. If a machine takes in more voltage than it can handle, it will explode. Do not connect a higher voltage source to a lower voltage without a transformer. It is fine to connect a lower voltage source to a higher voltage.

Amperage - The amount of packets of voltage. For each amp of a certain voltage, it can run a machine of said voltage at max power. So 1A = 1V and 2A = 2V, but at 2V it is still at said voltage tier and will not blow up machines. Certain machines may require more amps to be able to run. Machines will not explode for recieving too many amps. Cables and wires that cannot hold enough amps flowing through it will be destroyed.

Cables & Loss - To know how many amps the 1x version of a cable or wire can carry, hover over it in JEI. The amount of amps a cable or wire can hold is equal to Bx where B is the number next to x in JEI and x is equal to the amount of amps the 1x cable or wire can hold. Cables and wires that are not superconductors will have loss per amp per block. Cables will always have less loss than wires except for superconductors, where the wire version will give zero loss anyways. Example: A tin cable has 1 loss, if using a 2x tin wire, it will have 2V lost per block traveled since 2x tin wire holds 2A. Last thing to mention is that powered wires will hurt the player but cables will not, this does not apply to superconductors as you will not get damaged by the wire version.

Overclock - If a machine is processing a recipe that is a lower than itself, the recipe will be overclocked, and it will take 4x the energy while being 2x as fast. Certain multiblocks may follow different rules to this.

§lRF:EU:AE ratio is 1:1:1

Here is a detailed explanation on the EBF:

First, the energy hatches can be made to take in a specific amount of amps ranging from 2 amps to 128 amps. Here you make 2 2A hatches because 4A of LV power is equal to 1A of MV power, which is needed to process your first aluminium.

Second, every material that goes through the EBF has a certain heat requirement noted in JEI. Cupronickel coils have a heat capacity of 1700K.

Third, as noted by the tooltip, you will get EU/t discount depending on how much extra heat capacity your EBF has. Furthermore, with enough heat capacity over the minimum, your recipe will recieve a "perfect" overclock, where instead of it being 4x energy for 2x faster processing, it is 4x energy for 4x faster processing.

Fourth, early on, you can perform maintenance for a multiblock in one of 2 ways: you have all the tools required to perform maintenace, then click the maintenance square in gui, or you can just make some tape and do the same. Make sure all your multiblocks have no maintenance problems.
